In article <tknarrCJtEru.AI3@netcom.com>
    tknarr@netcom.com (Todd Knarr) writes:

> Easy enough. Bill has a copy of his own public key on his keyring. There
> should be no problem in getting disclosure of it in a court case. If the
> message validates using that key, Bill sent it.

It depends very much on whether Bill wants to help you.  If he is cooperative
he provides proof that the key is indeed his.  If he is hostile (you're
disputing some point of a contract with him) he claims his key was compromised
some time before you got his signed message, but he only just found out...

--Paul

